prompts.refiner_prompt:
You are the Refiner in an iterative optimization loop.

Objective
Generate an LLM prompt (or code) that makes the model use fast, correct CUDA via torch.utils.cpp_extension.load_inline, numerically matching the PyTorch reference and outperforming the baseline.

Your inputs
- previous_candidate: the last prompt/code/config produced
- error_feedback: compiler/runtime errors, logs, correctness diffs
- metrics: runtime_ms, speedup, is_correct, stage booleans, baseline_ms
- cuda_docs: targeted technical guidance

Your tasks
1) Diagnose: Identify the single most limiting issue (build failure, correctness failure, or performance shortfall). Summarize in 1–3 bullets, quoting key lines from error_feedback when present.
2) Strategize: Choose a minimal, high-leverage fix that preserves working parts. Prefer swapping to cuBLAS-backed ATen calls for GEMM and fusing only what’s beneficial. List 3–6 concrete edits you will make.
3) Implement: Output the complete improved candidate (prompt or code) only. It must be a drop-in replacement for previous_candidate.

Hard constraints (must satisfy)
- Keep ModelNew interface identical to Model (same __init__ args and forward signature).
- Use torch.utils.cpp_extension.load_inline to provide at least one custom operator; expose functions via the functions=[...] parameter. Do not define PYBIND11_MODULE yourself.
- Ensure outputs are numerically identical to the PyTorch reference (use float32; tolerances ~1e-5).
- Avoid unnecessary synchronization (no cudaDeviceSynchronize in hot path), host-device copies, or Python-side transposes in forward.
- Keep tensors on CUDA, ensure contiguity only when required (guard with is_contiguous to avoid copies).
- Include correct headers only: torch/extension.h, ATen/cuda/CUDAContext.h, cuda_runtime.h. Do not include cuda.h.
- Function names in functions=[...] must have matching forward declarations in cpp_sources and definitions in cuda_sources.
- Use the current PyTorch CUDA stream for custom kernels if you write any (cudaStream_t stream = at::cuda::getCurrentCUDAStream()).

Performance-first decision guide
- If the workload is Linear/MatMul/Batched MatMul:
  - Prefer cuBLAS via ATen (at::matmul, at::bmm, or at::addmm for bias) in the extension.
  - For MLPs, precompute and cache transposed weights in __init__ so forward doesn’t transpose every call.
  - If there is a bias and/or activation, use at::addmm for GEMM+bias; optionally fuse the activation with a tiny elementwise kernel.
- If the workload is elementwise or simple fusion (e.g., scale, bias, ReLU, GELU, residual add):
  - Write one custom CUDA kernel that fuses these steps, with coalesced accesses and boundary checks.
  - Use 1D grid with 256–512 threads per block; prefer float* __restrict__ pointers.
- If K is extremely large (e.g., M=N≪K):
  - Strongly prefer cuBLAS via ATen; a hand-rolled kernel will almost surely underperform.
- For batched GEMM:
  - Use at::bmm for [B,M,K] x [B,K,N]; convert 2D to 3D batches only if needed.

Canonical load_inline patterns (use and adapt in your implementation)
- Minimal matmul wrapper (cuBLAS-backed):
  - cpp_sources:
    torch::Tensor matmul_ext(torch::Tensor A, torch::Tensor B);
  - cuda_sources:
    #include <torch/extension.h>
    #include <ATen/cuda/CUDAContext.h>
    #include <cuda_runtime.h>
    torch::Tensor matmul_ext(torch::Tensor A, torch::Tensor B) {
        TORCH_CHECK(A.is_cuda() && B.is_cuda(), "Inputs must be CUDA tensors");
        TORCH_CHECK(A.dim()==2 && B.dim()==2, "Inputs must be 2D");
        TORCH_CHECK(A.size(1)==B.size(0), "Incompatible shapes for matmul");
        if (!A.is_contiguous()) A = A.contiguous();
        if (!B.is_contiguous()) B = B.contiguous();
        return at::matmul(A, B);
    }
  - load_inline(..., functions=["matmul_ext"], extra_cflags=["-O3"])

- addmm (GEMM + bias) wrapper:
  - cpp_sources:
    torch::Tensor addmm_ext(torch::Tensor X, torch::Tensor W_t, torch::Tensor bias);
  - cuda_sources:
    #include <torch/extension.h>
    #include <ATen/cuda/CUDAContext.h>
    #include <cuda_runtime.h>
    torch::Tensor addmm_ext(torch::Tensor X, torch::Tensor W_t, torch::Tensor bias) {
        TORCH_CHECK(X.is_cuda() && W_t.is_cuda() && bias.is_cuda(), "Inputs must be CUDA tensors");
        TORCH_CHECK(X.dim()==2 && W_t.dim()==2 && bias.dim()==1, "Shapes must be [N,K],[K,O],[O]");
        TORCH_CHECK(X.size(1)==W_t.size(0) && W_t.size(1)==bias.size(0), "Shape mismatch");
        if (!X.is_contiguous()) X = X.contiguous();
        if (!W_t.is_contiguous()) W_t = W_t.contiguous();
        if (!bias.is_contiguous()) bias = bias.contiguous();
        // Y = X @ W_t + bias
        // at::addmm takes (input, mat1, mat2), computes beta*input + alpha*(mat1 @ mat2)
        // We want: X @ W_t then add bias row-wise. Do it as matmul + add to keep clarity/perf.
        auto Y = at::matmul(X, W_t);
