- Quote 1–2 key lines if error_feedback exists (e.g., “cuda.h: No such file” or shape mismatch).
- If all stages passed but speedup <= 1.0, call it a performance shortfall and briefly name the suspected cause (e.g., “naive conv kernel vs cuDNN”, “Python-side transpose”, “extra copies”).

2) Strategize (3–6 bullets):
- Propose a minimal, high-leverage fix that preserves working parts.
- Prefer cuBLAS/cuDNN-backed ATen calls for GEMM/conv; fuse only light elementwise ops.
- Avoid adding new kernels unless they measurably reduce memory traffic (e.g., fused bias/activation).
- Ensure no Python-side transposes/copies in forward; cache transposed weights in __init__.
- Keep tensors on CUDA, guard contiguity with is_contiguous, and avoid synchronizations.

3) Implement:
- Output ONLY the complete improved candidate (prompt or code). It must be a drop-in replacement for previous_candidate.
- When producing code:
  - Keep ModelNew interface identical to Model (same __init__ args and forward signature).
  - Build the extension once (module scope or __init__) and cache the handle; don’t rebuild per forward.
  - Use torch.utils.cpp_extension.load_inline with functions=[...] and do NOT define PYBIND11_MODULE yourself.
  - Headers allowed: torch/extension.h, ATen/cuda/CUDAContext.h, cuda_runtime.h (do NOT include cuda.h).
  - Exposed function names must match declarations in cpp_sources and definitions in cuda_sources exactly.
  - Use the current PyTorch CUDA stream for launches: cudaStream_t stream = at::cuda::getCurrentCUDAStream().
  - Ensure float32 numerics and correctness within ~1e-5.
  - Avoid host-device copies, .cpu(), .numpy(), .item(), or cudaDeviceSynchronize in the hot path.
  - Guard contiguity: only call .contiguous() when needed.

Performance-first decision guide
- If workload includes Linear/MatMul/Batched MatMul:
  - Replace any hand-written matmul with cuBLAS-backed ATen calls in the extension:
    - matmul_ext(A, B) -> at::matmul(A, B)
    - addmm_ext(X, W_t, bias) -> at::matmul(X, W_t).add_(bias)
    - bmm_ext(A3D, B3D) -> at::bmm(A3D, B3D)
